//seeing small differences between colors of wounds/infections can be significant for a diagnosis
//even for non-colorblind people

/*
the brain does differential calculus (DFT) of wavelength-overlapping trichromatic input 
(or of (nearly) bichromatic for colorblindness)
, which can be amplified, by filtering some wavelengths (with expensive sunglasses)
, by mostly filtering "pure rgb colors" and non-yellow

the trick to counter colorblindness is to filfer out pure RGB colors
so that only CMY remains unfiltered

the interpolation between that increases a derivative
- most Types of colorblind people can barely differentiate purple/cyan/pink from other colors
unless you filter out "near purple/cyan" wavelengths
, with sunglasses that only remove (near pure) geen blue (and near infraRed, but not pure 400nM red)
*/

/*
Trying to simulate how Enchroma glasses filter out some wavelengths, 
to help differenciating between the remaining (unfiltered) wavelengths.

this translates rather poorly to an hsv rgb color space, 
for VacuumTube, LCD or OLED displays, but it sill works, kinda.

"Protan" is "red-green colorblindness"
where cells that should measure red do only measure green instead.
Owr where the loval maximum of red and green are significantly closer together.
This is not binary,
but a gradient with percentage of lacking the ability to distinguish red.

all vision comes down to a gradient of wavelengths, on a linear hue-gradient
but wavelengths get mixed (the brain does Fourier-Transform the input from the eyes).
all colorblindness boils down to a limitation of one domains of a 3d color space.
If the hue of 2 mixed colors is (nearly) the same,
the differentiation of mixed wavelengths gets tricky, or impossible.
the dotproduct is a bitch like that!
basically, color blindness applies a 3d to 2d matrix transform with no inverse:
 https://www.shadertoy.com/view/MdSGRW

Human cells are not too good in distinguishing wavelengths.
because there is a lot of frequency overlap between cells 
,that peak in measuring green, and cells that peak in measuring red.

Human vision does automatic diferentiation and Fourier Analysis from input of the eyes.
  https://www.shadertoy.com/results?query=derivative+arithmetic
between the input from 1, 2 or 3 cell types to estimate hue and brightness.
The differenciation between red and green 
is more prone to rounding errors due to a lot of overlapping.

this sloppy simulations visualizes how the filter increases contrast
between purple and blue
and between "shades of green".

We want to enghance an inverse, therefore we filter out the RGB main colors
, to nehanche the remaining  mixed CMY coplors

EnChroma glasses filter out wavelengths that are 
further AROUND the local maximum that human cells measure.
The (mlocal maximum) peak wavelengths of the primal colors are unfiltered, 
but wavelengths a bit above and below become invisible (or diminished to 10%).
therefore you see sharper hues, that are easier to differenciate.

In hue, this filters out the colors around red, green and blue. 
It reduces ALMOST PURE red and green down to 10% 
It reduces ALMOST PURE red and violet     to  0% (for color balance)
while PURE red, green violet are still at 100%

Then the brain can easier differenciate between the filtered input
and more easily distinguish colors between the peaks.
Better distinguishing colors between the main-color-peaks 
enables red-green colorblind people to distinguish orange from green.
Better distinguishing colors between the main-color-peaks 
enables red-green colorblind people to distinguish blue   from purple.
*/

#define phi (sqrt(5.)*.5+.5)


//hard c0 discontinuious step() filter:
#define EnHsv
#define EnHsvIntensity (sin(iTime*phi)*.5+.5)
//#define EnHsvIntensity 1.


//softer c1 dicsontinous piecewise filter: 
#define EnRgb
#define EnRgbIntensity (sin(iTime*5.)*.5+.5)

/*
EnRgb does
color.rgb=EnChromaRgb(color.rgb);
To kind of simulate how that same filter 
enables to focus on certain color frequencies 
by by diminishing the 3 main colors.

Purple|magenta, yellow and cyan "shine" a lot more 
by diminishing all other colors.

This can help dorctors to make better diagnoses

RedGreen colorblind people 
can only differenciate between 2 cell inputs.
and this color filter enables SOME them to pass SOME colorblind-tests 
as if they are not (as much) colorblind.

Because natural light is a mix of colors, the amount unfiltered colors
that still pass trough these glasses
helps them differenciate the color of orange carrots from green apples.
*/

/*

Natural (outdoor) light is more mixed in wavelengths 
than (indoor) lcd or led display light.
since this is 100% lcd/led, sorted by hue, this looks very silly:

A way to aid colorblind people to better distinguish more hues is
to block out the wavelengths that are in between the peaks 
of SML (short, medium,long wavelength)-receptor wavesforms.

*/

const float eps = 0.0000001;

vec3 hsv2rgb( in vec3 c )
{
    vec3 rgb = clamp( abs(mod(c.x*6.0+vec3(0.0,4.0,2.0),6.0)-3.0)-1.0, 0.0, 1.0 );
    return c.z * mix( vec3(1.0), rgb, c.y);
}

vec3 hsl2rgb( in vec3 c )
{
    vec3 rgb = clamp( abs(mod(c.x*6.0+vec3(0.0,4.0,2.0),6.0)-3.0)-1.0, 0.0, 1.0 );
    return c.z + c.y * (rgb-0.5)*(1.0-abs(2.0*c.z-1.0));
}

vec3 rgb2hsv( in vec3 c)
{
    vec4 k = vec4(0.0, -1.0/3.0, 2.0/3.0, -1.0);
    vec4 p = mix(vec4(c.zy, k.wz), vec4(c.yz, k.xy), (c.z<c.y) ? 1.0 : 0.0);
    vec4 q = mix(vec4(p.xyw, c.x), vec4(c.x, p.yzx), (p.x<c.x) ? 1.0 : 0.0);
    float d = q.x - min(q.w, q.y);
    return vec3(abs(q.z + (q.w - q.y) / (6.0*d+eps)), d / (q.x+eps), q.x);
}

vec3 rgb2hsl( vec3 col )
{
    float minc = min( col.r, min(col.g, col.b) );
    float maxc = max( col.r, max(col.g, col.b) );
    vec3  mask = step(col.grr,col.rgb) * step(col.bbg,col.rgb);
    vec3 h = mask * (vec3(0.0,2.0,4.0) + (col.gbr-col.brg)/(maxc-minc + eps)) / 6.0;
    return vec3( fract( 1.0 + h.x + h.y + h.z ),              // H
                 (maxc-minc)/(1.0-abs(minc+maxc-1.0) + eps),  // S
                 (minc+maxc)*0.5 );                           // L
}

//reduce s and v of some hue ranges
vec3 EnChromaHsv(vec3 c){

 if (c.x> 80./255.&&c.x<100./255.)c.yz*=.1;//hues from  80/255 to 100/255 filtered
 if (c.x>150./255.&&c.x<190./255.)c.yz*=.1;//hues from 150/255 to 190/255 filtered
 if (c.x>217./255.)c.yz*=.0;       //remove ultraviolet for color balance
 if (c.x< 12./255.)c.yz*=.0;       //remove infrared    for color balance
 return c;
}

//reduce rgb values of some ranges, similar to EnChromaHsv(), but
//not quite how human vision works, still helps "visualizing"
//how this apparently enhanches yellow, and mostly filters out green.
vec3 EnChromaRgb(vec3 c){//this is not too pretty
 if(c.b<.6)c.b*=.1;
 if(c.r<.3)c.r*=.1;
 if(c.r+c.g<.7){c.r*=.1;c.g*=.1;}
 return c;
}

